SIMPLE: lustration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lustration
<hw>Lus*tra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>lustratio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>lustration</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of lustrating or purifying.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And holy water for <qex>lustration</qex> bring.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Antiq.)</fld> <def>A sacrifice, or ceremony, by
which cities, fields, armies, or people, defiled by crimes, pestilence,
or other cause of uncleanness, were purified.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lustre</ent>⟦br⟧
